[0.000, "o", "ed with code 1\u001b[39m                                                                                                                                                \u001b[49m\u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n\u001b[48;2;240;232;232m                                                                                                                                                                           \u001b[49m\u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n \u001b[1m\u001b[3m\u001b[38;2;108;108;108mConsidering test strategy\u001b[39m\u001b[23m\u001b[22m                                                                                                                                                 \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n                                                                                                                                                                           \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n \u001b[3m\u001b[38;2;108;108;108mI think I need to fix the tests, maybe in step 2.5, but I can still implement step 2.2 and address tests later. Each branch should ideally pass after every commit, so it \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n \u001b[3;"]
[0.000, "o", "38;2;108;108;108mseems wise to ensure each step is passing before moving forward. I might only modify tests enough to reflect changes in behavior, but that’ll leave step 2.5 partially    \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n \u001b[3;38;2;108;108;108mdone. Perhaps I can mark 2.2 as complete once the tests are green, but I’ll need additional tests later. I'm still undecided on how to produce deterministic failures.\u001b[39m\u001b[23m    \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n                                                                                                                                                                           \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n \u001b[1m\u001b[3m\u001b[38;2;108;108;108mAnalyzing RNG output\u001b[39m\u001b[23m\u001b[22m                                                                                                                                                      \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n                                                                                                                                                                           \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n \u001b[3m\u001b[38;2"]
[0.000, "o", ";108;108;108mI'm currently looking at tests that expect a late-life failure at RNG 99. It seems the hard stepwise chance at 48 months gives a 16% probability, which might not be      \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n \u001b[3;38;2;108;108;108menough for RNG 99. I need to inspect the RNG output for state 99, and it might be beneficial to consider an older tick at 59 months, which still falls under index 4. If  \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n \u001b[3;38;2;108;108;108mI look at 60 months, it corresponds to index 5 with a 32% chance. I should calculate this using a small script.\u001b[39m\u001b[23m                                                           \u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n\u001b[48;2;232;240;232m                                                                                                                                                                           \u001b[49m\u001b[0m\u001b]8;;\u0007\r\r\n\u001b[48;2;232;240;232m \u001b[39m\u001b[1m$ node --input-type=module - <<'EOF'\u001b[22m                                                                                                                     "]
